711745f-a.text:
W. 23rd Street, north side, east from Thirteenth (left), to
Eleventh (right) Avenues, as viewed northeastward from a point
at W. 22nd Street near the North (Hudson) River. In the right
foreground is a small park with cabs at the westerly side of
same, awaiting passengers from the Erie Railroad ferry that docks
at this point. The 11 story Zinn Building seen, is at the S.E.
corner of Eleventh Avenue and W. 25th Street. To the left margin
is a 2 story frame structure that bears a sign identifying it
as Godwins Hotel. This is at the N.E. corner of Thirteenth
Avenue and W. 23rd Street and was replaced by the 4 story garage
shown in the other views. No. 2 is from a similar angle and shows
this feature prominently. No. 3 is northwestward from Eleventh
Avenue and 22nd Street and has the ferry house at its left margin.
Subsequently the West side Express Highway will loop across the
park to continue northward on Thirteenth Avenue and thereby follow
the westerly edge of Manhattan.
September 1911
View 2: April 22, 1931
View 3: April 2, 1929.
1. Geo. L. Balgue.
2&3.P.L. Sperr

710605f-a.text:
11th Avenue, at the N. W. corner of W. 23rd Street, showing a
"diner" located there, surrounded by the yards and shops of the
New York Railway Company. At the right is the 9-story Baltimore
and Ohio Railroad freight station and storage warehouse on 26th
Street.
View 2, being several years later, shows the absence of the
streetcar yards,and the new Starrett Lehigh Building. The latter
occupies the entire 26th to 27th Street block.
March 3, 1929
December 26, 1936
P. L. Sperr

711744f-a.text:
West 23rd Street, east from Eleventh Avenue, showing
pavement conditions during the street car track removal
program of the W.P.A. the elevated roadbed shown
carries the New York Central trains and is on this side
of Tenth Avenue. Beneath same, in the background appears
the Ninth Avenue "El" station. Between these two features
is the massive apartment row, London Terrace.
June 2, 1937
W.P.A. photo
Five Boroughs Project

711743f-a.text:
West 23rd Street, west from Eleventh Avenue, showing the terminus of this crosstown thoroughfare at the North River.  Sweeping diagonally across the park at the left, is the elevated West Side Vehicular Highway.  This obscures the lower portions of the Lackawanna Railroad Ferry, tho the tower atop appears.  Incidentally this faces on Thirteenth Avenue, there being no Twelfth Avenue at this point.  View 2 is limited to the north side of 23rd Street extending between these two thoroughfares.
June 2, 1937
Aug. 25, 1940

W.P.A. photo
Five Boroughs Inperative
P.L. Sperr

710606f-c.text:
11th Avenue, from W. 23rd (right) to 24th (left) Streets, as
viewed eastward across the cleared westerly side of same and
showing buildings that front on the easterly side. The cleared
area is the former New York Railway Company yard site. The
building bearing the Spears sign, is on the south side of W. 23rd
Street midway between 10th and 11th Avenues.
View 3 is northeastward towards 24th Street.
December 5, 1936
April 3, 1937
January 6, 1933
P. L. Sperr
